    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>I Pay My Taxes. They Should, Too.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael A Katz letter, commenting on Sept 13 article on abusive corporate tax shelters, says IRS has obligation to aggressively pursue tax cheats</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Shelter Plan Tests the Limits of the Tax Law'' (front page, Sept. 13):</p>
        <p>I was dismayed to read this article during this particular week, in which I am required, as a self-employed professional, to write a check representing a substantial portion of my income for my quarterly estimated income tax payment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Shelter Plan Tests the Limits of the Tax Law'' (front page, Sept. 13):</p>
        <p>I was dismayed to read this article during this particular week, in which I am required, as a self-employed professional, to write a check representing a substantial portion of my income for my quarterly estimated income tax payment.</p>
        <p>The Internal Revenue Service has an obligation to honest taxpayers to deal aggressively with those who by cynical gaming of the tax system avoid paying their fair share of the cost of government because they think they will not get caught.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL A. KATZ  Chatham, N.J., Sept. 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
